<@U3MTJRAQL>, I completely understand and to and extent, agree with your assessment. I’m not usually one for durdly cards, but a cheap, aggro mitigating commander that has an etb is something that can help a bunch of different style of decks flourish, especially when they didn’t have a good option before. 

This can facilitate a blink strategy in Jeskai, or a solid control deck, a more solid superfriends deck that is a bit more pillowforty than Kykar, but not as oppressive as Narset, it could facilitate Kiki/Twin combo decks, etc.

It is definitely useless in one on one, but the ability to sway early game pressure is something that we haven’t had before, and can help new decks in those colors.
That being said, one could (validly) argue that some of those decks shouldn’t need or be getting help, but I digress. I think having some options that are quite broad is a boon right now.

I think that's a succinct way to describe my issue, yeah. I don't think those decks needed help. Combo and durdlevalue "two ships passing in the night" gameplay isn't what I want in Magic. It shouldn't be four games of solitaire and then someone wins. I look to the precon commanders to encourage more interactivity between players, especially combat, so Sevinne and holographic diamond feel antithetical to the direction I'd like the format to go.

I think that’s a fair issue to have with the card. I could very well like it on paper right now, but hate it in practice. Or even worse, like it in practice for generally non-interactive reasons. 

I’m hoping for something more in the Kykar level of cool than Sevinne in regard to the 3rd Commander.
I’ll give it to the wall though, it definitely hits the flavor of a wall. :joy:
